				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${a^*}\sqrt 2$$\end{document} ordering of the parent perovskite, whereas the dimension along the b axis is (2a*n + x), where a* = 6.3 Å is the lattice parameter of MAPbI3, x ~ 8 Å is the thickness of the (BA)22+ bilayer, and n is the number of perovskite layers.Fig. 1
Two-dimensional perovskites and the corresponding crystal structures. a Photograph of sample powders in capillary tubes, showing bandgap blueshift upon decreasing the layer number, n. b Crystal structures viewed along the (100) crystallographic projection. The elements in the crystals are represented by different colors: Pb in dark green, I in purple, N in dark blue, H in yellow, and C in light green

Figure 2a shows wavelength-dependent third harmonic generation (THG) from n = 1–∞ as well as AgGaSe2, when wavelength was varied over a broad range of 1200 nm to 2700 nm. It is interesting to observe fluctuating THG responses of the 2D perovskites, when the THG wavelength, λTHG, approaches their bandgaps. Detailed THG scans revealed that it arises from resonance effects at both the fundamental gap and the exciton level (Fig. 2b). Considering the narrower bandgap of the 3D perovskite (grey squares), it is expected that MAPbI3 exhibits a stronger THG response than the wider bandgap AgGaSe2 (dots). It is, however, very surprising that the 2D perovskites (n = 1–4) having even wider bandgaps yield much stronger THG responses than AgGaSe2 and the 3D perovskite (n = ∞) as well, throughout the broad IR regime, i.e., λ > 2100 nm (λTHG = λ/3 > 700 nm). For example, the n = 1–4 members of the series outperform the benchmark IR NLO material, AgGaSe2, by more than an order of magnitude even with significant fundamental absorption in the range of λ = 2100 nm–2500 nm arising from excitation of organic cations (Supplementary Figs. 3 and 4).Fig. 2
